{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501969"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:37:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:37:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1814"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1814"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.11,0.05,0.11,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109514"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1814"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91886"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"3382"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19213"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40967"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109514"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with severe epigastric pain which started after an episode of heavy binge drinking 48 hours earlier. His blood pressure is 110/60 mmHg and pulse rate is 130/min. His abdomen is distended, with marked epigastric tenderness and scant bowel sounds. The serum lipase is 750 U/L (0-60).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to analgesia, which one of the following is the most important next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous fluids","Nasogastric decompression","Broad spectrum antibiotics","CT abdomen","Chest X-ray"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESevere epigastric pain after an episode of heavy binge drinking and serum lipase \u22653 times the upper limit of the normal range (10-60 U/L) is suggestive of pancreatitis. The recognised causes of acute pancreatitis can be remembered by the mnemonic \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0022I GET SMASHED\u0022:\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003EI\u003C/strong\u003Ediopathic, \u003Cstrong\u003EG\u003C/strong\u003Eallstones, \u003Cstrong\u003EE\u003C/strong\u003Ethanol, \u003Cstrong\u003ET\u003C/strong\u003Erauma, \u003Cstrong\u003ES\u003C/strong\u003Eteroids, \u003Cstrong\u003EM\u003C/strong\u003Eumps, \u003Cstrong\u003EA\u003C/strong\u003Eutoimmune, \u003Cstrong\u003ES\u003C/strong\u003Ecorpion poison, \u003Cstrong\u003EH\u003C/strong\u003Eypercalcaemia, \u003Cstrong\u003EH\u003C/strong\u003Eypertriglyceridaemia, \u003Cstrong\u003EE\u003C/strong\u003ERCP, and \u003Cstrong\u003ED\u003C/strong\u003Erugs(eg, thiazides, valproic acid). Put in perspective the two important causes are gallstones (40 - 70%) and alcohol (25 - 35%). The other causes are all relatively uncommon and perhaps the most important of them to remember is post-ERCP. The diagnosis of acute pancreatitis can be made if the patient has \u22652 of the following characteristics:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESevere epigastric pain radiating to the back\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EElevated serum amylase, or serum lipase \u22653 times the upper limit of the normal range\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImaging findings consistent with pancreatitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the abdominal distension and paucity of bowel sounds is probably due to paralytic ileus, which has occurred as a result of the inflammatory process within the abdominal cavity. The standard of care for a patient with uncomplicated acute pancreatitis is the use of supportive measures. This includes appropriate analgesia, rehydration with IV fluids (if required), and enteral nutrition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENasogastric decompression is indicated in patients with intestinal obstruction to decompress the gut. Intestinal obstruction is associated with increased bowel sounds in the acute presentation. This patient\u0027s clinical and lab findings are more suggestive of acute pancreatitis. If the patient felt nauseated, then a nasogastric tube might be considered - however, the initial step in management must be to get the pain under control and administer intravenous fluids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActive measures such as antibiotics and gut rest have no proven role in the management of acute pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImaging will not influence the management of acute pancreatitis. Plain radiology is of limited value in the visualisation of soft tissue pathologies and its only place in this situation would be if free intraperitoneal gas was suspected. A CT scan may be required if there is diagnostic uncertainty, clinical evidence of deterioration, or a potential complication.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The initial treatment of a patient with acute pancreatitis must revolve around supportive care, namely, analgesia and fluid replacement."],"references":["Nesvaderani M, Eslick G, Cox M. Acute pancreatitis: update on management. Medical Journal of Australia. 2015;202(8):420-423. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25929504/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91886"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1814"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91886"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-22T08:07:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-22T08:08:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1814"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109514"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"e